04:21.360 --> 04:22.361
Mmm-hmm.

04:27.240 --> 04:28.241
Oh.

04:28.800 --> 04:31.451
This is much more to my liking.

04:32.080 --> 04:33.286
WOMAN: Looks good.

04:35.520 --> 04:37.249
Thank you for your approval.

04:40.240 --> 04:42.447
Yeah. Yeah, we keep
them on the floor,

04:42.520 --> 04:43.851
so that's perfect.

05:30.920 --> 05:32.081
Thanks, dean

06:41.000 --> 06:42.161
(EXHALES)

06:51.640 --> 06:53.927
(HARRIET MUMBLING)

06:58.560 --> 07:00.767
(INDISTINCT CHATTER
OVER RADIO)

07:00.840 --> 07:02.410
(SIRENS BLARING)

07:04.160 --> 07:07.004
Hello, Ms. Lauler,
I'm Dr. Morgan.

07:09.280 --> 07:13.046
It says here
this was an accident.

07:15.360 --> 07:19.843
Well, do you think I'm lying
or just simply can't read?

07:19.960 --> 07:21.530
Ms. Lauler, I'm just
doing my job.

07:21.640 --> 07:23.768
These gowns?
You call these gowns?

07:24.720 --> 07:26.802
If I was wheeled out
in a wheelchair,

07:26.880 --> 07:28.803
would you call that my chariot?

07:28.880 --> 07:31.201
Ma'am...
Don't call me "ma'am."

07:31.280 --> 07:32.770
You never call
a woman "ma'am."

07:32.880 --> 07:35.087
That makes her feel old.
I'm sorry.

07:35.240 --> 07:37.208
You're sorry?
Oh, you're so sorry.

07:37.280 --> 07:39.362
You washed down four clonazepam

07:39.440 --> 07:41.761
with a bottle of red wine.

07:41.840 --> 07:45.447
Yes. I was sleepy
and I was thirsty.

07:47.680 --> 07:50.809
You don't strike me
as the type of person

07:50.880 --> 07:53.008
who does anything
by accident, okay?

07:53.080 --> 07:55.321
That's what it seems like to me.

07:55.400 --> 07:57.084
What I'm experiencing here.

07:57.480 --> 08:00.131
So, I'm going to
do some tests. Okay?

08:00.200 --> 08:02.965
And if you have a problem
with that, I don't care.

08:03.080 --> 08:05.003
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

08:43.120 --> 08:44.167
(GASPS)

09:28.800 --> 09:30.848
(INDIE ROCK SONG PLAYING)

09:45.200 --> 09:46.326
Hi, this Anne Sherman.

09:50.720 --> 09:52.085
(TELEPHONE RINGS)

09:52.160 --> 09:54.322
(SONG CONTINUES PLAYING
ON HEADPHONES)

10:18.120 --> 10:19.929
(TELEPHONE RINGING
IN DISTANCE)

10:28.880 --> 10:29.881
Do you know who I am?

10:30.080 --> 10:31.206
Yes.

10:32.440 --> 10:34.488
Uh, no.
Your predecessor did.

10:34.560 --> 10:36.562
Your predecessor
knew me very well.

10:36.640 --> 10:39.246
My father?
Lam Harriet Lauler.

10:39.560 --> 10:41.881
And for the better part
of the last 25 years

10:42.000 --> 10:43.604
this newspaper
stayed in the black

10:43.680 --> 10:44.806
because of the media buys

10:44.880 --> 10:46.564
that I purchased every month.

10:47.720 --> 10:49.051
Lauler Advertising.

10:49.400 --> 10:52.051
Of course. Uh, what can I
do for you, Ms. Lauler?

10:52.240 --> 10:54.242
I request a formal introduction.

10:56.200 --> 10:57.201
Okay.

10:58.200 --> 10:59.486
<i>(CLEARS THROAT)</i>

10:59.920 --> 11:03.242
My name is Ronald Odom.
I'm the editor-in-chief.

11:03.680 --> 11:05.091
I attended
the school of journalism

11:05.160 --> 11:06.366
at Ohio University.
Mr. Odom.

11:06.560 --> 11:08.801
I married Katie Sparrow.
She kept her name.

11:08.920 --> 11:10.843
Mr. Odom. I do not require

11:10.920 --> 11:12.570
the formal introduction to you.

11:14.880 --> 11:16.450
Hey. Hey.
Wha...

11:16.920 --> 11:18.046
Come with me.
Why?

11:18.120 --> 11:19.360
'Cause I'm your boss.

11:19.440 --> 11:21.488
Are you firing me?
You should be so lucky.

11:21.560 --> 11:22.766
Come on, come on, come On.

11:31.520 --> 11:32.965
Ms. Lauler,
this is Anne Sherman.

11:33.320 --> 11:34.401
Ms. Sherman.

11:34.480 --> 11:35.970
Let us have the room, please.

11:39.600 --> 11:41.489
Please sit down.
Oh, I'm cool.

11:41.640 --> 11:42.721
(DOOR CLOSES)

11:42.800 --> 11:45.201
Well, be that as it may,
I wish you would sit down

11:45.280 --> 11:48.090
because I have a job offer
to discuss with you.

11:48.520 --> 11:50.045
(STAMMERS) <i>I</i> have a job.

11:50.160 --> 11:51.605
(CHUCKLES) Hmm.

11:51.680 --> 11:52.920
Sit down, Ms. Sherman.

12:07.280 --> 12:08.805
Lois Schenken was a bitch.

12:09.920 --> 12:11.046
"Lois Schenken,

12:11.160 --> 12:13.083
"a tireless
animal rights advocate,

12:13.160 --> 12:15.766
"passed away last night
at the age of 78."

12:15.880 --> 12:18.247
Right, Lois Schenken.
I wrote that.

12:18.320 --> 12:19.321
Yes.

12:19.920 --> 12:23.163
Do you know why Lois Schenken
loved animals so much?

12:23.680 --> 12:25.250
Because people hated her.

12:25.400 --> 12:27.482
They hated her parties,
they hated her gossiping,

12:27.600 --> 12:29.409
and they hated
her costume jewelry.

12:29.480 --> 12:33.485
Only homeless dogs could bear
to be around Lois Schenken

12:33.560 --> 12:34.891
for longer than seven minutes.

12:34.960 --> 12:36.325
Well, the people that I spoke to

12:36.440 --> 12:38.647
had nothing but kind things
to say about her.

12:38.760 --> 12:41.001
She was dead and
they were being polite.

12:41.560 --> 12:44.370
"Eugene Baker, with a song
not just in his heart,

12:44.440 --> 12:45.885
"but always on his lips.

12:45.960 --> 12:48.122
"Eugene Baker sang his way

12:48.200 --> 12:50.726
"into the lives
of all who met him."

12:51.080 --> 12:52.923
Do you know why he sang so much?

12:53.840 --> 12:55.046
He was a drunk.

12:55.160 --> 12:56.256
Okay, well, that's not something

12:56.280 --> 12:57.456
that I was going to write
in his obituary.

12:57.480 --> 12:58.527
"After a long illness,

12:58.600 --> 13:00.409
"Mary Ramos passed
away this morning.

13:00.480 --> 13:02.289
"She left an indelible
mark on all..."

13:02.360 --> 13:04.200
(SCOFFS) Yeah, right.
She had syphilis, I know.

13:04.240 --> 13:07.084
That's not something that
you want to memorialize.

13:08.240 --> 13:09.526
I knew these people.

13:10.640 --> 13:12.290
I'm... I'm sorry
for your losses.

13:12.600 --> 13:14.204
No, these were awful people.

13:14.600 --> 13:17.206
Well, I'm...
I'm not sorry then.

13:17.560 --> 13:21.042
But you made them sound as
though they were magnificent.

13:21.400 --> 13:24.290
You made their lives
sound full of achievement.

13:25.200 --> 13:27.009
That's what you'll
be doing for me.

13:28.360 --> 13:30.044
You want me
to write your obituary?

13:30.680 --> 13:31.681
That's what I want.

13:31.760 --> 13:35.731
Okay. Well, lam
the obituary writer,

13:36.200 --> 13:37.326
so when the time comes,

13:37.400 --> 13:38.811
I will be writing your obituary.

13:38.920 --> 13:40.922
I want you to write it now.

13:43.000 --> 13:44.001
Huh.

13:45.000 --> 13:46.126
Is Ron coming back?

13:46.280 --> 13:47.805
That's the wrong question.

13:48.040 --> 13:49.769
The right question is, "Why?"

13:50.200 --> 13:51.201
Why?

13:51.920 --> 13:53.570
Good question.
Thanks.

13:53.640 --> 13:55.483
Ms. Sherman,
I'm a reasonable woman.

13:55.560 --> 13:57.847
I have never been
surprised about anything.

13:57.920 --> 13:59.160
And I've never found myself

13:59.240 --> 14:01.083
in a situation
that I couldn't handle.

14:01.160 --> 14:02.650
So, as a reasonable woman,

14:02.720 --> 14:05.166
the thought of leaving
my obituary to chance

14:05.280 --> 14:07.044
is completely
unreasonable to me.

14:07.240 --> 14:08.571
But that is what everybody does.

14:08.640 --> 14:10.696
That is what people have been
doing for hundreds of years.

14:10.720 --> 14:12.006
If I had motivated myself

14:12.120 --> 14:13.724
by what other people
thought and did,

14:13.800 --> 14:15.096
I would not have achieved
what I've achieved.

14:15.120 --> 14:16.485
And I've achieved a great deal.

14:17.280 --> 14:20.682
How my achievements
are memorialized by you

14:20.760 --> 14:22.922
is of great interest to me.

14:24.240 --> 14:25.446
Okay.

14:26.080 --> 14:28.162
Here's the names
of a few hundred people.

14:29.160 --> 14:31.561
I've taken the trouble
to alphabetize them.

14:31.960 --> 14:34.804
Also, restaurants are listed
that they might like to go to

14:34.880 --> 14:36.120
while they discuss me with you.

14:36.440 --> 14:37.521
What...

14:38.320 --> 14:39.685
What about family?

14:42.480 --> 14:45.165
I have a daughter, and I haven't
spoken to her in many years.

14:46.120 --> 14:47.167
Okay.

14:47.280 --> 14:50.443
There's an ex-husband.
He's a jackass.

14:50.760 --> 14:52.046
(SCOFFS)

14:52.160 --> 14:55.130
Right, all right. What's... What's
the timeline that we're looking at?

14:55.200 --> 14:56.326
Monday.

14:56.640 --> 14:58.005
No.
Yes.

14:58.080 --> 15:00.447
I want it by Monday.
I have plans.

15:01.960 --> 15:03.121
(SCOFFS)

15:03.200 --> 15:05.521
You're excused. Go.
That's what I want.

15:25.320 --> 15:29.041
Hey. She puts the
"bitch" in obituary.

15:29.120 --> 15:31.771
I understand.
I don't think you do, Ron.

15:33.000 --> 15:34.764
You got to do it.
What? Why?

15:34.840 --> 15:36.080
Because at one time,

15:36.160 --> 15:38.242
this woman was a real
friend of the paper.

15:38.320 --> 15:40.607
And if she were to extend
that friendship

15:40.680 --> 15:42.250
at the time of her passing,

15:42.320 --> 15:43.896
that would be extremely
helpful to all of us.

15:43.920 --> 15:46.082
What are you saying?
I'm saying look around.

15:46.160 --> 15:48.049
I mean... (SIGHS)
We're in trouble here.

15:48.120 --> 15:50.043
The digital age wasn't a fad.

15:50.120 --> 15:52.043
I mean, who knew, right?
Everybody.

15:52.680 --> 15:53.727
Why do you all say that?

15:54.200 --> 15:55.725
Are you saying
I could lose my job?

15:55.920 --> 15:57.570
I'm saying we could
all lose our jobs.

15:58.640 --> 16:01.405
Okay. So what am I
supposed to do?

16:02.000 --> 16:03.240
Make her happy.

16:07.960 --> 16:10.122
(SIRENS BLARING IN DISTANCE)

16:23.920 --> 16:25.240
(INDIE ROCK SONG
PLAYING ON RADIO)

16:47.280 --> 16:49.123
MAN: <i>(ON RADIO) This is
Robin Sands for KOXA.</i>

16:49.200 --> 16:50.361
Hello, Robin Sands.

16:50.440 --> 16:51.680
<i>Playing independent music</i>

16:51.760 --> 16:53.967
<i>for independent minds.
For independent minds.</i>

16:54.040 --> 16:55.485
(INDIE ROCK SONG
CONTINUES PLAYING)

17:11.520 --> 17:13.647
ANNE: <i>How long were
you and Harriet married?</i>

17:13.880 --> 17:15.882
Um, a little over 19 years.

17:16.000 --> 17:18.002
And, you know,
when we got married,

17:18.079 --> 17:19.969
she did not take my name.

17:20.040 --> 17:21.280
Did you know that?

17:21.839 --> 17:25.287
Who did that back then
but Harriet Lauler?

17:25.599 --> 17:28.001
Yeah. I get the
impression that she...

17:28.560 --> 17:31.006
Control is very
important to Harriet.

17:31.960 --> 17:35.248
Well, she asked you
to write her obituary

17:35.320 --> 17:36.810
while she is still alive.

17:37.520 --> 17:39.045
Yeah, I think it's safe to say

17:39.160 --> 17:41.640
that control is very
important to Harriet.

17:42.280 --> 17:43.327
Was she always like that?

17:45.040 --> 17:48.442
Well, you gotta understand
that when she started out,

17:48.520 --> 17:50.010
it was a different world.

17:50.480 --> 17:52.448
I mean, the men that
she had to work with.

17:52.840 --> 17:54.649
Men she had to work for.

17:54.960 --> 17:56.200
She had to be twice as good,

17:56.280 --> 17:58.601
twice as smart,
twice as forceful.

17:59.040 --> 18:01.008
(CHUCKLES) And she was, too.

18:02.160 --> 18:04.401
See... She always thought
she was right.

18:04.920 --> 18:06.001
Always.

18:06.080 --> 18:09.289
But the one thing that made
her light up with excitement

18:10.000 --> 18:11.923
was finding out
that she was wrong.

18:12.920 --> 18:13.921
Yeah, see...

18:14.600 --> 18:16.921
If you were willing to go
toe-to-toe with Harriet,

18:17.000 --> 18:19.082
prove that you were right
and she was wrong,

18:19.200 --> 18:20.247
she loved that.

18:20.720 --> 18:23.485
And she would laugh.
(CHUCKLES)

18:23.560 --> 18:26.211
Now, she never said,
"I'm wrong."

18:26.680 --> 18:28.728
But hearing that laugh...

18:31.320 --> 18:32.890
That was enough for me.

18:33.720 --> 18:34.926
What about your daughter?

18:35.920 --> 18:37.445
Hey, if you were
looking for somebody

18:37.520 --> 18:39.443
to say something nice
about Harriet,

18:39.520 --> 18:41.284
don't ask Elizabeth.

18:41.680 --> 18:42.920
Trust me on that one.

18:46.680 --> 18:47.886
Good luck.

18:51.840 --> 18:53.001
You'll need it.

18:54.760 --> 18:55.886
<i>My name is Anne Sherman.</i>

18:55.960 --> 18:57.376
<i>I'm</i> calling <i>from
the Bristol Gazette.</i>

18:57.400 --> 18:59.607
<i>I'd like to talk to you
about Harriet Lauler.</i>

18:59.680 --> 19:02.490
"If I want your opinion,
I will give it to you,"

19:02.560 --> 19:04.005
that's what she told me.

19:04.120 --> 19:05.406
So you know Harriet how?

19:05.960 --> 19:07.530
I was her gynecologist.

19:08.520 --> 19:10.363
So how did you become
Harriet's hairdresser?

19:10.440 --> 19:13.011
She walked in the door
and said, "Cut my hair."

19:13.160 --> 19:14.685
Okay...
And I was like,

19:14.760 --> 19:17.969
"I'm actually cutting somebody
else's hair right now."

19:18.600 --> 19:20.443
And she asked
the woman to leave.

19:21.000 --> 19:22.536
ANNE: I'm <i>calling</i>
from the Bristol Gazette.

19:22.560 --> 19:24.722
I'd like to talk to you
about Harriet Lauler.

19:24.800 --> 19:26.211
(DIAL TONE)

19:26.280 --> 19:27.406
Hello?

19:28.440 --> 19:30.169
I learned a long time ago

19:30.240 --> 19:35.406
if you don't have anything
nice to say about someone,

19:36.440 --> 19:37.771
say nothing at all.

19:45.040 --> 19:47.486
She insisted
on examining herself.

19:47.680 --> 19:49.444
Her diagnosis, always correct.

19:50.680 --> 19:52.444
I had to give her
her co-pay back.

19:55.600 --> 20:01.607
Just a, uh,
hateful, hateful woman.

20:02.960 --> 20:04.291
I hated her.

20:05.400 --> 20:06.970
I hated her so much.

20:08.840 --> 20:10.080
So much.

20:13.800 --> 20:15.160
ANNE: <i>What do you
think of Harriet?</i>

20:15.840 --> 20:21.131
I've worked very hard in
therapy not to think of her.

20:21.920 --> 20:23.729
If there's just one thing
you could say

20:23.800 --> 20:24.961
about her that's nice.

20:25.800 --> 20:27.404
One thing nice.

20:27.480 --> 20:30.324
If she were dead, that would be nice.
How's that?

20:33.840 --> 20:36.286
She's like a human black cloud.

20:36.360 --> 20:38.488
Angriest vagina
this side of China.

20:38.680 --> 20:42.162
"Give me the wafer this way."
"Hand me the wine that way."

20:42.240 --> 20:43.321
"That wine is horrible."

20:44.040 --> 20:46.168
Like, nothing?

20:46.320 --> 20:47.481
Zippo.

20:52.000 --> 20:53.490
(GROANS) I don't...

21:14.280 --> 21:15.725
So this is what you wrote.

21:15.800 --> 21:16.801
It's a first draft.

21:16.920 --> 21:18.570
No. This is a
first paragraph.

21:18.760 --> 21:19.966
It's succinct.

21:20.200 --> 21:21.804
It's one paragraph.

21:22.040 --> 21:23.769
It's to the point
and I think that's good.

21:24.000 --> 21:25.365
No, it's the life of a loser.

21:25.440 --> 21:26.601
(SCOFFS) I wouldn't say that.

21:26.720 --> 21:27.856
This is the life of a nobody.

21:27.880 --> 21:29.166
I definitely wouldn't say that.

21:29.800 --> 21:31.450
Then what would you say?

21:31.560 --> 21:33.403
Because you certainly
have not captured

21:33.520 --> 21:35.807
an impressive life,
an important life.

21:36.360 --> 21:38.124
I did my best.

21:38.480 --> 21:40.881
That is really unfortunate
for both of us.

21:41.880 --> 21:43.450
Well, I didn't have
a lot to work with.

21:43.560 --> 21:44.925
No, you had my life
to work with.

21:45.120 --> 21:46.929
And I did the best
that I could with it.

21:49.760 --> 21:51.171
(SIGHS) Huh.

21:51.600 --> 21:54.683
How grossly I overestimated
your talent as a writer.

21:56.360 --> 21:57.441
With all due respect...

21:57.560 --> 22:00.928
Oh, now you respect me.
I was not really sure of that.

22:01.000 --> 22:03.480
The problem
isn't with my writing.

22:03.880 --> 22:05.245
What is the problem?

22:05.320 --> 22:07.482
It's the subject.
You are the problem.

22:07.560 --> 22:08.561
Excuse me?

22:09.040 --> 22:10.883
You are the problem.

22:11.360 --> 22:12.771
What? How dare you?

22:12.840 --> 22:15.764
No, I... I'm sorry.
How dare you?

22:15.840 --> 22:18.525
No one, and I mean nobody,

22:18.600 --> 22:21.171
had one nice thing
to say about you.

22:21.240 --> 22:24.403
No colleagues, no friends.
Certainly no family.

22:24.480 --> 22:25.720
What did you just say?

22:26.000 --> 22:28.082
I said certainly no family.

22:28.360 --> 22:29.361
Hmm.

22:29.960 --> 22:31.291
Get out of my house.

22:31.760 --> 22:34.730
I'm just... I'm just
being honest with you.

22:34.800 --> 22:38.771
You expected these people
to sing your praises?

22:38.840 --> 22:41.411
I mean, you're way off.

22:41.560 --> 22:43.483
Get out of my house!

22:44.080 --> 22:45.206
Now!

22:49.120 --> 22:50.360
(DOOR CLOSES)

22:57.320 --> 22:58.367
Bitch!

23:01.520 --> 23:02.806
(STARTS ENG I N E)

23:14.080 --> 23:15.286
(SCOFFS)

23:35.280 --> 23:36.850
(HORNS BLARING)

23:37.240 --> 23:40.767
(SIRENS BLARING IN DISTANCE)
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

23:44.000 --> 23:45.525
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

23:51.120 --> 23:52.804
(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

23:54.000 --> 23:55.576
Harriet, what are you...
What are you doing here?

23:55.600 --> 23:57.887
I do not wish to be
sodomized in the hallway.

23:57.960 --> 23:59.644
Do you know what time it is?

23:59.720 --> 24:00.846
Sit down, please.

24:01.360 --> 24:03.010
We need to talk.

24:03.200 --> 24:04.326
What is this shit?

24:04.400 --> 24:06.004
These are obituaries

24:06.080 --> 24:08.970
from newspapers
all over the country.

24:12.160 --> 24:13.321
I want you to read them

24:13.400 --> 24:15.801
and see what other
obituary writers are doing.

24:15.880 --> 24:18.121
Wow, I'm sorry you
don't like what I wrote,

24:18.200 --> 24:21.363
but that's... That was just
me writing about your life.

24:21.480 --> 24:23.642
But my life is not over. Yet.

24:25.640 --> 24:27.165
Now, I have determined

24:27.240 --> 24:29.129
there are four
essential elements

24:29.200 --> 24:31.282
to a really great obituary.

24:31.600 --> 24:34.046
(SCOFFS) ls that right?
That's right.

24:34.440 --> 24:38.650
One, the deceased should
be loved by their families.

24:38.720 --> 24:39.801
Right.

24:39.880 --> 24:43.726
Two, the deceased should be
admired by their coworkers.

24:43.800 --> 24:45.370
I... I know.

24:45.480 --> 24:47.721
Three, the deceased must have

24:47.840 --> 24:50.571
touched someone's
life unexpectedly.

24:50.840 --> 24:54.242
And if said person was
a minority or a cripple,

24:54.920 --> 24:56.570
so much the better.

24:57.680 --> 24:59.284
(SIGHS)
Okay, and the fourth?

24:59.360 --> 25:02.842
And the fourth,
that's the wild card.

25:02.920 --> 25:05.207
I do not know
what my wild card is.

25:05.840 --> 25:07.046
Wild card?

25:07.120 --> 25:11.284
Yes, a statement of
such breadth and wonder

25:11.360 --> 25:14.682
that it's the opening
line of the obituary.

25:14.760 --> 25:17.764
For example,
"A noted lover of arts,

25:17.840 --> 25:20.320
"Bonnie Lee Johnson
passed away today."

25:21.200 --> 25:22.406
Right, right.

25:22.680 --> 25:25.650
"A three-time state
ballroom dancing champion,

25:25.720 --> 25:27.688
"Lou Mendoza
died last night."

25:27.760 --> 25:29.967
Okay, I have a question.
Yes.

25:30.320 --> 25:32.129
Well, four to be exact.

25:33.760 --> 25:34.761
Four?

25:36.000 --> 25:39.163
Oh. Four. Mmm. Family?

25:39.440 --> 25:40.885
My child and I have not had

25:40.960 --> 25:43.008
any contact for several decades.

25:43.080 --> 25:45.048
My colleagues,
as you have discovered,

25:45.120 --> 25:47.930
are not exactly beating down
my door to sing my praises.

25:48.120 --> 25:50.202
I don't know any
crippled black kids.

25:51.120 --> 25:54.567
And four, I have no idea
what the wild card would be.

25:54.640 --> 25:56.005
Those are the questions.

25:56.640 --> 25:58.722
Yes. And you're going to
help me find the answers.

25:59.240 --> 26:00.685
Uh, you don't say.

26:01.000 --> 26:02.161
Oh, yes.

26:03.120 --> 26:06.761
You're going to help
shape a legacy

26:06.840 --> 26:09.605
instead of just transcribing it.

26:12.000 --> 26:14.651
I bet you have not been
offered that very often.

26:16.840 --> 26:18.968
To write a story
before it's over.

26:19.240 --> 26:20.321
(SCOFFS)

26:20.400 --> 26:23.006
That's what I've been talking
about, Anne. Yeah.

26:24.360 --> 26:26.647
So you're going to change
your life, like, right now?

26:27.520 --> 26:28.681
Exactly.

26:30.280 --> 26:33.443
Do you find any problem
in procuring me

26:33.520 --> 26:35.488
a disadvantaged youth to mold?

26:35.920 --> 26:38.400
Oh, um, Home Depot is probably

26:38.480 --> 26:39.970
getting another
shipment in soon.

26:40.040 --> 26:41.565
The shelves will be stocked.

26:42.200 --> 26:44.009
Sarcasm, the wit of the witless.

26:44.120 --> 26:46.521
Condescension,
the repartee of the rude.

26:47.120 --> 26:48.963
Sorry. Shit. Sorry.

26:49.040 --> 26:52.726
No, no. Never apologize
for speaking your mind.

26:55.080 --> 26:56.491
Thanks for coming.

26:59.080 --> 27:00.809
(LATIN HIP-HOP SONG PLAYING)

27:13.600 --> 27:15.125
B-2.

27:19.720 --> 27:21.882
I'm going to find the
woman that I spoke to.

27:22.080 --> 27:23.684
Wanda? Hey.

27:23.760 --> 27:25.808
(CHILDREN CHATTERING)

27:31.640 --> 27:33.051
WANDA: Walking.

27:34.440 --> 27:37.125
Harriet, this is...
This is Wanda Barnes.

27:37.200 --> 27:38.964
She runs the program
for at-risk kids.

27:39.240 --> 27:42.528
Hello, Wanda. Who runs the
program for at-risk visitors?

27:43.720 --> 27:47.167
Ms. Lauler, no need to worry.
This is a safe space.

27:47.360 --> 27:48.964
I'm very reassured.
Thank you.

27:49.280 --> 27:51.442
I know the children,
especially the girls,

27:52.040 --> 27:53.405
would greatly enjoy it

27:53.480 --> 27:55.289
if you would come in
and speak with them.

27:55.760 --> 27:57.046
You want Harriet to speak

27:57.120 --> 27:58.849
with a group
of at-risk children?

27:59.480 --> 28:00.925
I think the kids would love it.

28:01.040 --> 28:02.690
Or, I'm just throwing
this out there,

28:02.760 --> 28:04.444
she could write you
a big, fat check.

28:05.200 --> 28:07.487
Am I supposed to talk
to your boss yet again?

28:08.160 --> 28:11.084
I'm... I'm just saying that
money makes a difference.

28:11.480 --> 28:13.130
Am I right, Wanda?
(STAMMERING)

28:13.200 --> 28:14.326
Well, certainly...

28:14.400 --> 28:17.210
A woman who wrote a check
to a small community center

28:17.280 --> 28:19.362
died last night, Harriet Lauler,

28:19.440 --> 28:20.885
leaving behind a legacy

28:20.960 --> 28:23.930
of unfulfilled goals
and half measures.

28:25.080 --> 28:27.287
Can I circle back
on that big, fat check?

28:32.640 --> 28:34.802
<i>HARRIET: So I hear
you kids are at risk.</i>

28:36.040 --> 28:38.122
All kids are at risk, you know.

28:39.040 --> 28:40.565
Show me a kid who is not at risk

28:40.640 --> 28:43.405
and I'll show you a kid
who will be a nobody.

28:44.800 --> 28:47.167
Taking risks is what
life is all about.

28:47.360 --> 28:51.490
I took a risk. I went to college.
(CHUCKLES)

28:52.080 --> 28:53.491
And in my day,

28:53.560 --> 28:56.769
no man wanted to marry
a woman who was educated.

28:56.880 --> 28:59.167
No man wanted to marry
a woman who worked.

28:59.840 --> 29:02.491
No man wanted a woman
that he worked for.

29:02.960 --> 29:04.530
But my favorite was

29:04.600 --> 29:07.683
no one wanted to marry
a woman in business.

29:07.760 --> 29:10.286
But those were the risks
I was willing to take.

29:10.360 --> 29:13.250
Why? Why did you
take those risks?

29:14.560 --> 29:16.164
Because there was no way

29:16.240 --> 29:19.483
I was not going to
live up to my potential.

29:21.120 --> 29:24.249
So you have to ask
yourselves this question,

29:25.560 --> 29:28.689
are you willing to take a risk
to do something stupid?

29:31.400 --> 29:33.164
Or are you willing
to take a risk

29:33.240 --> 29:35.242
at doing something great?

29:38.800 --> 29:40.040
(APPLAUDING)

29:47.760 --> 29:49.489
WOW. (CHUCKLES)

29:50.040 --> 29:52.160
I think you gave those girls
something to think about.

29:52.480 --> 29:55.086
Seem to be quite skilled
at selling Pablum

29:55.160 --> 29:57.083
to a bunch of pre-teen punks.

29:57.200 --> 29:58.804
Great, Pablum.

29:58.880 --> 30:00.644
But you know that
speech is not enough.

30:01.000 --> 30:02.047
We have to come back

30:02.120 --> 30:04.327
and we have to find
our own hooligan

30:04.400 --> 30:07.006
who will benefit most
from my wisdom

30:07.600 --> 30:10.171
and that will be
the unexpected person

30:10.240 --> 30:11.571
whose life I touch.

30:26.800 --> 30:28.086
Hey, kiddo.
Hey, Dad.

30:28.320 --> 30:29.640
Didn't know
you were coming today.

30:30.000 --> 30:31.096
Leigh Ann's not here. Right?

30:31.120 --> 30:33.646
(SIGHS) No, she's got her class.
The coast is clear.

30:33.920 --> 30:35.001
Ta-da!
Oh, look.

30:35.080 --> 30:36.256
Just what I always
wanted. Dirty clothes.

30:36.280 --> 30:37.611
There you go.
Thank you very much.

30:48.440 --> 30:50.602
Laundry in?
Yep.

30:51.080 --> 30:52.127
Great.

30:53.080 --> 30:54.081
You hungry?

30:54.400 --> 30:55.561
No thanks.
Oh, come on.

30:56.200 --> 30:57.280
Let me make you a sandwich.

30:57.840 --> 31:00.969
I'm okay. Thank you.
I'm really not hungry.

31:07.200 --> 31:09.043
I got you that tea you like.

31:10.120 --> 31:11.884
Um, thanks.

31:12.840 --> 31:14.569
You're still doing
the essay thing?

31:14.920 --> 31:15.967
Yeah.

31:17.040 --> 31:18.485
How're they shaping up?

31:18.960 --> 31:20.610
Slow but steady.

31:22.320 --> 31:24.448
So when was it you first
started working on those?

31:24.560 --> 31:25.561
I can't remember.

31:25.640 --> 31:27.210
I'm just treading water, okay?

31:27.880 --> 31:29.848
No pressure.
I'm just... You know.

31:31.400 --> 31:33.562
You might want to say
pencils down at some point

31:33.640 --> 31:35.040
and actually let
somebody read them.

31:35.480 --> 31:36.811
(SIGHS) Like you?

31:39.120 --> 31:40.406
Yeah, I'm sure
they're wonderful.

31:42.680 --> 31:43.806
They're not.

31:44.680 --> 31:45.886
Well... (SIGHS)

31:47.000 --> 31:50.083
See, now I think you're just
being too hard on yourself.

31:53.360 --> 31:55.408
Would you consider yourself
to be the kind of person

31:55.480 --> 31:57.050
who takes risks in their life?

31:59.280 --> 32:00.281
Nah.

32:01.720 --> 32:02.767
No.

32:04.880 --> 32:06.484
No, your mother...

32:07.440 --> 32:10.603
I got to admit. She was
more of a risk taker.

32:10.960 --> 32:12.564
So is that what
we're calling it?

32:13.680 --> 32:15.364
Well, it was a long time ago.

32:16.000 --> 32:17.081
Why not?

32:17.880 --> 32:19.689
Because that sounds like

32:19.760 --> 32:21.842
what she did to us
was almost noble,

32:21.960 --> 32:23.007
which it wasn't.

32:23.080 --> 32:26.527
Look, you don't have to
like what she did, okay?

32:27.600 --> 32:29.045
I mean, I didn't like it.

32:29.320 --> 32:33.484
But obviously she
wanted something else,

32:33.560 --> 32:34.925
and so she just went after it.

32:35.000 --> 32:37.082
So as long as she's,
like, living the dream,

32:37.160 --> 32:38.446
that's all that matters?

32:38.560 --> 32:42.007
Anne... (SIGHS) I'm happy.

32:42.480 --> 32:44.164
Good.
Okay? Finally.

32:45.520 --> 32:50.287
And I pray every single
day that you are too.

32:54.000 --> 32:55.411
(DOOR CREAKS)

34:02.200 --> 34:03.326
<i>ANNE: Hi. Excuse me,</i>

34:03.440 --> 34:06.046
is Mr. Samuels available
to talk for a minute?

34:06.360 --> 34:07.361
And you are?

34:07.480 --> 34:08.561
My name is Anne Sherman,

34:08.639 --> 34:10.400
I work for the <i>Bristol</i>
Gazette. I'm a writer.

34:10.880 --> 34:13.326
Good for you. What is
this in reference to?

34:13.400 --> 34:14.764
Harriet Lauler.

34:14.840 --> 34:17.969
RECEPTIONIST:
Actually, he isn't in today.

34:18.199 --> 34:20.567
I don't even know why I
asked who you were. No?

34:20.639 --> 34:21.687
He's not even here.

34:21.760 --> 34:24.331
He's not here? Okay.
Mmm-mmm.

34:24.480 --> 34:25.641
What about Mr. Schmidt?

34:25.719 --> 34:27.722
Mmm, sorry.

34:29.159 --> 34:30.456
So none of them are here.
Mmm-mmm.

34:30.480 --> 34:31.527
Great.

34:33.239 --> 34:35.846
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

34:41.239 --> 34:42.924
WANDA: Brenda! Brenda!

34:43.920 --> 34:45.216
You realize this
little stunt of yours

34:45.239 --> 34:46.764
will take weeks to fix?

34:46.840 --> 34:49.366
Don't need to be fixed.
My way is better.

34:49.480 --> 34:51.721
I know you think that,
but this is what libraries do.

34:51.800 --> 34:53.962
Just because that's
the way it's always been

34:54.040 --> 34:55.405
don't mean I give a shit.

34:55.520 --> 34:58.046
WANDA: There's nothing wrong
with the Dewey Decimal System.

34:58.120 --> 35:00.088
Having to write down
some six-digit number

35:00.200 --> 35:02.487
with a decimal
just to find a book,

35:02.560 --> 35:03.891
don't tell me that makes sense.

35:04.080 --> 35:05.809
What the fuck do I
need with the decimal?

35:06.200 --> 35:07.770
Just want to read a book.

35:07.840 --> 35:10.764
That's the juvenile delinquent
I'll put my mark on.

35:10.840 --> 35:12.376
You arranged every book
in alphabetical order.

35:12.400 --> 35:13.731
You should be thanking me.

35:15.280 --> 35:16.520
Hello.

35:19.040 --> 35:20.087
Uh, Wanda.

35:47.080 --> 35:50.004
You know, when you utter
profanity in public like that,

35:50.080 --> 35:52.447
you risk others thinking
that you're too uneducated

35:52.520 --> 35:54.090
to find the right words.

35:54.560 --> 35:55.891
Who the hell are you?

35:56.160 --> 35:58.208
How about, "I'm sorry.
Have we met before?"

35:58.520 --> 35:59.646
I ain't sorry.

35:59.760 --> 36:01.888
Just want to know who's
getting all up in my business.

36:02.240 --> 36:03.730
Well, I know
that I am the world's

36:03.800 --> 36:05.689
least qualified fairy godmother,

36:05.760 --> 36:08.604
but it is me who is getting
up all in your business.

36:08.840 --> 36:09.841
Da fuck?

36:09.960 --> 36:12.122
You see, instead of "Da fuck,"

36:12.200 --> 36:14.601
why don't you just
say, "Excuse me?"

36:16.360 --> 36:17.930
What do you want?

36:19.480 --> 36:20.891
What do you want?

36:21.640 --> 36:25.770
Oh, I see.
It's community service.

36:26.120 --> 36:28.851
You got busted for
drunk driving. Didn't you?

36:28.920 --> 36:31.366
Now, what on Earth
made you think that?

36:31.440 --> 36:33.249
You're white.
And you're here.

36:36.000 --> 36:37.001
This is true.

36:37.640 --> 36:39.802
However, I'm here
of my own accord.

36:39.880 --> 36:41.405
No obligation at all.

36:41.760 --> 36:42.886
To try to get to know you

36:42.960 --> 36:45.850
and to impart my considerable
breadth of knowledge.

36:45.920 --> 36:47.649
You want to teach me some shit.

36:50.960 --> 36:52.644
You want to teach me some stuff.

36:54.520 --> 36:56.010
Seems like we've already begun.

36:57.720 --> 36:59.484
(CHILDREN CHATTERING)

37:03.840 --> 37:05.968
Oh, shit. Sorry.
(HARRIET GROANS)

37:09.240 --> 37:10.241
HARRIET: Ugh.

37:13.440 --> 37:14.805
ANNE: Let me move this

37:15.680 --> 37:17.125
trash.

37:22.200 --> 37:23.440
What are you doing?

37:23.520 --> 37:25.602
This is a collection of essays.

37:26.000 --> 37:27.126
Yeah, they're mine.

37:27.200 --> 37:29.680
Am I supposed to assume that you
care about things... Christ.

37:29.760 --> 37:31.762
Besides writing
about dead people?

37:33.160 --> 37:34.440
You can assume
whatever you want.

37:34.560 --> 37:36.005
That's how I generally operate.

37:36.480 --> 37:38.130
Yeah, no shit.
What do you care?

37:38.920 --> 37:40.365
I never said I did care.

37:41.160 --> 37:44.084
Okay, well, in the interest
of me getting back to my life,

37:44.160 --> 37:46.561
what do... What do you
think your wild card

37:46.640 --> 37:48.210
could end up being?

37:48.600 --> 37:49.840
How about this?

37:50.520 --> 37:54.241
"Harriet Lauler, ultimate
lover of clean cars,

37:54.360 --> 37:58.331
"died this afternoon after
contracting a staph infection

37:58.400 --> 38:00.687
"from inside
a Volvo station wagon."

38:02.120 --> 38:03.121
All right.

38:03.840 --> 38:05.490
I'll take that as a "no."

38:06.920 --> 38:08.729
Get in the car!
No!

38:08.840 --> 38:09.841
All right, all right,

38:09.920 --> 38:11.680
I'm just going to
drive away with your purse.

38:12.800 --> 38:14.290
Put this trash back here.

38:16.040 --> 38:17.451
(ENGINE STARTS)
Bye.

38:26.280 --> 38:27.327
Ugh!

38:27.400 --> 38:28.640
That's what I thought.

38:30.440 --> 38:32.169
Oh, God.

38:40.200 --> 38:42.168
Would you like
to come in for some tea?

38:43.080 --> 38:46.084
What? Tea! Would
you like some tea?

38:47.040 --> 38:49.281
Sure.
Well, good. Come.

38:49.360 --> 38:50.361
Okay.

39:21.600 --> 39:23.250
ANNE: Holy shit, Harriet.

39:23.320 --> 39:25.891
Oh! I forgot I had those.

39:26.080 --> 39:27.320
You forgot you had

39:27.400 --> 39:29.448
an extensive collection
of records?

39:29.720 --> 39:30.721
Yeah.
What?

39:30.800 --> 39:34.009
You forgot about this?
(LAUGHS) Yes.

39:34.080 --> 39:37.846
God, '50s, '60s, '70s.

39:40.600 --> 39:45.049
Where's the rest? Did you...
Did you start collecting CDs?

39:45.120 --> 39:47.441
No. I'd rather listen
to elevator music.

39:47.560 --> 39:48.721
Why, because it's tinny,

39:48.800 --> 39:51.371
and there aren't enough
nuances in the mix?

39:52.000 --> 39:53.411
Very good, Anne.

39:53.800 --> 39:55.928
Yeah, thanks. Analog,
I know, all the way.

39:56.000 --> 39:57.240
I'm totally into it.

39:57.400 --> 40:00.847
(STAMMERS) If you don't
have a CD collection,

40:01.000 --> 40:04.607
then where's the rest
of your records?

40:05.040 --> 40:07.008
There isn't any rest.
That's it.

40:07.600 --> 40:08.601
Why?

40:08.680 --> 40:11.490
Why are you so interested
in this? Really?

40:11.560 --> 40:14.689
Yes, lam. (CHUCKLES)
I would like to know.

40:18.160 --> 40:19.241
When I was a kid,

40:19.320 --> 40:21.163
I loved to listen to the radio.

40:21.480 --> 40:22.891
I loved the disc jockeys.

40:22.960 --> 40:24.928
I loved what they chose to play.

40:25.280 --> 40:27.089
They would play something

40:27.360 --> 40:29.761
very exploratory
and I would think,

40:29.840 --> 40:31.080
"Yes, I like to go there."

40:31.160 --> 40:32.764
And I would listen to the music.

40:32.840 --> 40:35.684
Then they'd play
something really bad,

40:35.760 --> 40:37.000
like, almost violent,

40:37.120 --> 40:39.202
and I would take a look
at what I thought.

40:39.440 --> 40:41.886
See what I mean?
They were in control of,

40:43.040 --> 40:47.045
I guess, basically my
kind of budding imagination.

40:47.680 --> 40:50.411
Wait. So, um, who was
your favorite disc jockey?

40:50.520 --> 40:52.727
Bobby Dale. Bobby Dale.

40:53.360 --> 40:56.921
Eclectic taste.
Minimum patter.

40:57.120 --> 40:59.726
And really brilliant sequencing.

41:00.200 --> 41:04.444
But then, you know,
as with everything,

41:04.520 --> 41:06.921
music became business.

41:07.720 --> 41:09.563
And they put the music in a box.

41:10.120 --> 41:13.522
And then my disc jockeys
became computers.

41:14.280 --> 41:16.089
I didn't do it anymore.

41:16.560 --> 41:18.403
Yeah, but that still
exists, you know.

41:18.480 --> 41:21.927
I mean, this radio station
that I listen to, KOXA,

41:22.040 --> 41:23.849
that's exactly what
you're talking about.

41:23.960 --> 41:25.803
The DJs get to play
whatever music they want.

41:25.920 --> 41:29.527
They have complete control
over the music they play.

41:29.600 --> 41:31.648
It's amazing.
Harriet, you would love it.

41:31.720 --> 41:34.849
"KOXA, independent music
for independent minds.

41:34.920 --> 41:38.129
"Number 107.2 on the dial.
Number one in your heart."

41:38.720 --> 41:39.721
Hmm.

41:41.320 --> 41:42.401
Okay.

41:43.520 --> 41:44.567
Thanks.

41:46.960 --> 41:49.088
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

41:52.320 --> 41:53.401
Anne.

41:54.920 --> 41:56.206
Joe Mueller.

41:56.840 --> 41:58.604
I'm here about Harriet Lauler.

42:00.400 --> 42:02.050
<i>MAN</i> 1: <i>What could
the ad agency do</i>

42:02.120 --> 42:03.565
<i>to make the commercial better?</i>

42:03.640 --> 42:05.051
<i>MAN 2: Why are
the people cartoons?</i>

42:05.120 --> 42:06.360
<i>Is this an ad for kids?</i>

42:06.560 --> 42:08.056
MAN 1: <i>Well, no. As I
mentioned at the beginning,</i>

42:08.080 --> 42:10.003
<i>if this turned into
a real advertisement,</i>

42:10.080 --> 42:11.241
<i>they'd use real people.</i>

42:11.320 --> 42:12.416
<i>MAN 2: They should
use a celebrity.</i>

42:12.440 --> 42:13.521
<i>WOMAN: I love Shelley Long.</i>

42:13.600 --> 42:15.090
(ALL CHATTERING)

42:18.120 --> 42:19.724
<i>Oh, would you just shut up?</i>

42:20.480 --> 42:22.209
<i>I'm Harriet Lauler.</i>

42:22.280 --> 42:25.602
<i>I'm the creative director
of this agency.</i>

42:25.960 --> 42:28.281
<i>A creative director is in charge</i>

42:28.360 --> 42:30.124
<i>of the creative decisions</i>

42:30.200 --> 42:32.521
<i>you make in your company!</i>

42:32.880 --> 42:35.406
<i>Not other people, who sit around</i>

42:35.480 --> 42:39.804
<i>motivated by plates
of pizza and $15.</i>

42:40.160 --> 42:41.969
<i>No, you know what?
I'm not going to do this.</i>

42:43.200 --> 42:44.440
<i>Because it's stealing.</i>

42:44.920 --> 42:46.524
<i>You give me your money</i>

42:46.600 --> 42:49.604
<i>and this is what
you expect in return?</i>

42:50.000 --> 42:53.800
<i>It's bullshit. I Won't take
your money anymore,</i>

42:53.880 --> 42:56.087
<i>you spineless pieces of shit.</i>

42:56.160 --> 42:57.924
MAN 3: <i>Harriet.
Get her out of here.</i>

42:58.000 --> 43:00.446
<i>HARRIET: Get the fuck
off of me. You hack!</i>

43:03.120 --> 43:05.202
They just threw her out.

43:05.840 --> 43:06.887
Yeah.

43:06.960 --> 43:08.928
It's her company.
She started it.

43:10.000 --> 43:11.650
How can they do that?

43:12.240 --> 43:13.480
She scared them.

43:15.080 --> 43:16.127
Didn't like her.

43:16.200 --> 43:18.282
'Cause they couldn't
control her.

43:20.840 --> 43:22.649
Jesus Christ, man.

43:22.720 --> 43:23.926
Exactly.

43:25.520 --> 43:27.204
But you... You liked her?

43:28.880 --> 43:31.611
I respected her.
I feared her.

43:34.360 --> 43:36.124
Why did you show this to me?

43:41.520 --> 43:43.249
Guilt, maybe.

43:44.680 --> 43:45.727
Probably.

43:46.440 --> 43:48.044
She got screwed.

43:48.920 --> 43:50.729
I didn't open my mouth.

43:53.480 --> 43:55.608
(R&B MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)

43:58.720 --> 44:00.136
<i>MAN: (ON RADIO) They say
that the really great music</i>

44:00.160 --> 44:01.446
<i>can take you to those places</i>

44:01.520 --> 44:03.284
<i>that you could never
get to on your own.</i>

44:03.840 --> 44:05.001
<i>Well...</i>

44:05.120 --> 44:07.282
<i>This one definitely
does that for me.</i>

44:07.680 --> 44:11.571
<i>So whatever your journey is,
see where this one takes you.</i>

44:12.240 --> 44:13.651
<i>Robin Sands, KOXA.</i>

44:14.560 --> 44:15.925
(MUSIC CONTINUES PLAYING)

44:58.160 --> 45:00.606
(MUSIC PLAYING)
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

45:08.760 --> 45:13.288
Well, I wish to speak
to Robin Sands. Please.

45:13.560 --> 45:14.561
MAN: Yeah.

45:15.440 --> 45:17.408
Hi, I'm Robin.

45:17.800 --> 45:19.962
Yes, I'd like a job
as a disc jockey.

45:20.120 --> 45:21.360
(CHUCKLES)

45:23.480 --> 45:25.482
Uh, yeah. Um...

45:25.560 --> 45:27.005
I'm not really
looking at the moment.

45:27.360 --> 45:29.886
But I noticed that
your sound transmission

45:29.960 --> 45:31.485
is not compressed.

45:32.160 --> 45:33.605
(STAMMERING)
That's right. Yeah.

45:33.680 --> 45:36.081
Is that because of the
Teletronix tube that you use?

45:36.480 --> 45:38.403
Yeah, yeah. Absolutely right.
Mmm-hmm.

45:38.480 --> 45:40.280
Yeah, we couldn't afford
the big digital stuff

45:40.320 --> 45:42.000
even if we wanted it,
and we don't want it.

45:42.160 --> 45:44.003
Oh, I should hope not.
Damn right.

45:44.480 --> 45:45.686
And who are you?

45:45.840 --> 45:46.921
I'm Harriet Lauler,

45:47.000 --> 45:49.321
formerly of Lauler Advertising.

45:49.400 --> 45:52.051
I am an older woman,
as you might have gathered.

45:52.120 --> 45:53.929
But with age comes
certain attributes,

45:54.000 --> 45:57.482
and one of mine is I'm up
very early every morning.

45:57.560 --> 45:58.971
I would gladly take over

45:59.040 --> 46:02.010
the drive time slot
of Dawn Silver.

46:02.680 --> 46:05.650
Uh, I'm... I'm Dawn.
No, you're out.

46:06.560 --> 46:09.484
Your voice is thin and
your taste is pedestrian.

46:10.520 --> 46:12.522
And what kind of music
would you play?

46:12.680 --> 46:14.648
Robin, are you fucking kidding me?
Wait, just...

46:14.720 --> 46:16.643
Now, that is the wrong question.

46:17.040 --> 46:18.326
Is it?
Hmm.

46:20.040 --> 46:21.080
What's the right question?

46:21.200 --> 46:24.010
(CHUCKLES) The right question
would be what would I play

46:24.080 --> 46:26.526
<i>after</i> I <i>play Nina Simone's
Gin House Blues.</i>

46:27.600 --> 46:29.856
What would you play after you played
Nina Simone's Gin House <i>Blues?</i>

46:29.880 --> 46:31.291
Good question.
Thank you very much.

46:31.360 --> 46:34.011
I would play Very Special,
Duke Ellington.

46:34.080 --> 46:35.127
Great.

46:35.200 --> 46:37.965
Then I would play
Van Morrison, Ro Ro <i>Rosey.</i>

46:38.040 --> 46:40.805
Great. And I'd probably end
with something by The Kinks.

46:42.200 --> 46:43.201
You like The Kinks?

46:43.360 --> 46:45.601
Oh, the most underrated band

46:45.680 --> 46:46.681
of all time.
Of all time.

46:46.760 --> 46:48.536
That's what I keep saying.
I keep saying that.

46:48.560 --> 46:49.641
Don't I always say that?

46:49.720 --> 46:52.724
You see, Robin, anybody
can pick a good song.

46:52.840 --> 46:56.322
But a true disc jockey
is interested in the flow,

46:56.400 --> 46:59.927
in the sequencing,
in the block, if you will.

47:00.720 --> 47:02.131
I am very interested
in the block.

47:02.200 --> 47:03.201
And I'm very wealthy,

47:03.280 --> 47:05.169
so I do not have
to have a salary.

47:06.040 --> 47:08.168
Oh. Well, that's great.

47:08.960 --> 47:10.883
And who is this?
It's my intern.

47:11.160 --> 47:13.401
What up?
What up?

47:16.440 --> 47:18.727
All right,
Harriet Lauler, let's chat.

47:18.800 --> 47:21.406
Whoa. Let's do this.
Mmm.

47:22.120 --> 47:26.489
Did I just lose my job
to a 100-year-old woman?

47:27.760 --> 47:31.481
You know, as a general rule,
most people are idiots.

47:31.560 --> 47:32.561
Yeah.

47:32.640 --> 47:34.847
So when you're confronted
by an idiot,

47:35.200 --> 47:38.522
rather than make themselves
aware of their idiocy,

47:39.480 --> 47:42.563
it's best just to treat them
like a dumb, stupid child

47:42.680 --> 47:44.728
who doesn't know
any better, you know?

47:44.840 --> 47:46.683
So be patient
with the dummies, right?

47:46.800 --> 47:48.564
Exactly.
Yeah.

47:49.760 --> 47:51.120
(ROCKABILLY MUSIC
PLAYING ON RADIO)

47:59.640 --> 48:02.484
<i>(ON RADIO) This is
Harriet Lauler for KOXA.</i>

48:02.560 --> 48:05.882
<i>Playing independent music
for independent minds.</i>

48:05.960 --> 48:08.725
<i>Up next, we're kicking off
wild card weekend.</i>

48:15.520 --> 48:17.409
(FUNK SONG PLAYING)

48:38.800 --> 48:40.131
Harriet.

48:42.040 --> 48:43.644
Who's the
disc jockey? (LAUGHS)

48:44.080 --> 48:45.730
I... I'm stunned.

48:46.040 --> 48:49.044
No. I wanted to do
something like this

48:49.120 --> 48:50.849
and I just made it happen.

48:51.400 --> 48:53.880
Oh. Just like that?
Yes, of course.

48:55.760 --> 48:57.888
Can I... Can I
stay and watch?

48:57.960 --> 48:59.564
Go outside.
I got work to do here.

48:59.640 --> 49:01.165
You can watch from out there.

49:02.600 --> 49:03.806
Okay.

49:04.040 --> 49:06.361
(FUNK SONG CONTINUES PLAYING)

49:50.480 --> 49:51.481
(some ENDS)

49:51.560 --> 49:52.686
(SLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

50:35.040 --> 50:36.371
(CLICKS TONGUE)

50:36.840 --> 50:38.524
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

50:38.600 --> 50:40.682
Eddie Cochran
was a solid choice.

50:40.760 --> 50:42.489
(ALL APPLAUDING)

50:42.600 --> 50:44.682
Much respect to the rock block.

50:47.160 --> 50:48.605
Wild card.

50:48.680 --> 50:50.125
Much respect.

50:54.400 --> 50:55.686
So where is he taking you?

50:55.760 --> 50:58.286
(GASPS) No.
(CHUCKLES)

50:58.640 --> 50:59.721
Oh!

50:59.800 --> 51:02.007
Well, I orchestrated
the whole thing.

51:02.120 --> 51:04.851
(STAMMERING)
Why would you do that?

51:05.160 --> 51:07.242
It just felt like
something that I should do.

51:07.320 --> 51:09.971
No. You don't get to
control me, Harriet.

51:10.040 --> 51:12.407
Is he taking you somewhere nice?

51:12.480 --> 51:13.845
(SIGHS)

51:14.560 --> 51:16.085
We're going to The Cave
this weekend.

51:16.160 --> 51:19.926
The Cave! No. No. No.
Absolutely not.

51:20.000 --> 51:21.047
That is not the place.

51:21.160 --> 51:23.401
What you have to do is tell him

51:23.480 --> 51:24.925
to take you to Cafe Bouchon.

51:25.160 --> 51:28.289
What did I just say?
I heard what you just said.

51:28.360 --> 51:30.283
But a proper date
really does include

51:30.360 --> 51:31.964
a very, very nice dinner.

51:32.080 --> 51:34.162
This is not a proper date.
We are going as friends.

51:34.240 --> 51:35.321
That is what I told him.

51:35.960 --> 51:37.371
Why would you say that to him?

51:38.520 --> 51:41.285
Because I don't want
to ruin what we have.

51:41.480 --> 51:43.005
But you just met.
You have nothing.

51:43.200 --> 51:44.531
I have his show.

51:46.840 --> 51:47.841
Ah.

51:48.280 --> 51:49.850
Oh. Well, there you have it.

51:51.000 --> 51:52.047
What do I have?

51:52.200 --> 51:53.964
(LAUGHS)

51:54.040 --> 51:57.522
It just shows me
what kind of child you are.

51:57.640 --> 51:59.165
(SIGHS)

51:59.240 --> 52:00.480
"Anne Sherman

52:00.920 --> 52:02.843
"died from lethal
injection last night

52:02.920 --> 52:04.136
"for the murder
of Harriet Lauler.

52:04.160 --> 52:06.049
"Her last words were,
'It was worth it."'

52:06.120 --> 52:07.804
(ENGINE STARTS)

52:07.880 --> 52:09.166
Very good, Anne.

52:09.920 --> 52:11.046
Excellent.

52:19.120 --> 52:20.485
RONALD: Hey,
I was looking for you.

52:20.840 --> 52:22.968
How's our favorite
senior citizen?

52:23.520 --> 52:24.521
She's a handful.

52:24.720 --> 52:26.927
I remember the stories
my father used to tell.

52:27.000 --> 52:28.684
Scary, scary stories.

52:29.120 --> 52:30.770
Thanks for passing
her off on me.

52:30.880 --> 52:32.211
Well, it wasn't my choice.

52:32.280 --> 52:35.329
You know, she chose you.
You should feel...

52:35.400 --> 52:37.129
No. Don't say "honored."

52:38.320 --> 52:40.607
Fair enough.
How about this? Thank you.

52:41.280 --> 52:44.409
Thank you for at least
giving me the chance

52:44.480 --> 52:45.845
to not be the first Odom

52:45.920 --> 52:48.730
to completely destroy
his family's legacy.

52:49.400 --> 52:50.401
Hmm.

52:50.880 --> 52:52.325
Not going to say,
"You're welcome."

52:52.400 --> 52:53.845
I'm just not going to say it.

52:54.080 --> 52:55.844
(ROCKABILLY MUSIC PLAYING)

53:00.760 --> 53:03.286
This is Harriet Lauler
saying good morning.

53:18.040 --> 53:19.166
(LAUGHS)

53:43.360 --> 53:44.964
(SLOW JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING)

53:49.200 --> 53:50.281
(DOORBELL RINGS)

53:55.120 --> 53:58.010
(GASPS) on. (LAUGHS)

53:58.080 --> 53:59.491
Hello, boss.

53:59.840 --> 54:02.047
I have missed that so much.

54:02.120 --> 54:03.451
Come in.

54:03.520 --> 54:04.521
Liquid lunch?

54:04.600 --> 54:07.046
Ooh! My favorite.
I remember.

54:07.120 --> 54:08.121
Oh...

54:09.240 --> 54:11.288
Terrace. Go.

54:12.000 --> 54:14.082
(BOTH LAUGHING)

54:19.440 --> 54:22.683
Oh, Joe. Now tell me
why you're really here.

54:41.480 --> 54:42.811
That's the original.

54:44.800 --> 54:46.165
Oh, God.

54:47.760 --> 54:48.886
Those bastards.

54:48.960 --> 54:51.042
(SCOFFS) They still are.

54:51.400 --> 54:54.688
Wasn't exactly my finest hour
either, though, was it?

54:56.200 --> 54:59.886
You were trying to protect
the agency. Your agency.

55:01.280 --> 55:03.647
You were a goddamn hero.

55:06.160 --> 55:07.161
Hmm.

55:08.840 --> 55:11.491
Harriet Lauler, goddamn hero.

55:12.360 --> 55:13.407
I like it.

55:15.880 --> 55:18.042
So that's the original.
Any copies?

55:18.880 --> 55:21.770
Yeah, I made a copy
for your friend Anne.

55:27.760 --> 55:29.091
Anne has seen this?

55:32.160 --> 55:33.685
<i>HARRIET: (ON TAPE)
in your company!</i>

55:34.080 --> 55:36.526
<i>Not other people, who sit around</i>

55:36.600 --> 55:41.083
<i>motivated by plates
of pizza and $15.</i>

55:41.160 --> 55:43.481
<i>No, you know what?
I'm not going to do this.</i>

55:44.360 --> 55:47.364
<i>Because it's stealing.
It is stealing.</i>

55:47.440 --> 55:48.885
<i>You give me your money</i>

55:48.960 --> 55:52.089
<i>and this is what
you expect in return?</i>

55:52.440 --> 55:56.081
<i>It's bullshit. I Won't take
your money anymore,</i>

55:56.160 --> 55:58.401
<i>you spineless pieces of shit.</i>

55:58.480 --> 56:00.050
MAN: <i>Harriet.
Get her out of here.</i>

56:00.120 --> 56:02.726
<i>HARRIET: Get the fuck
off of me. You hack!</i>

56:05.400 --> 56:07.416
No, I like to think of myself
as a curator, you know?

56:07.440 --> 56:11.240
Bringing new artists
and songs to my listeners

56:11.320 --> 56:13.209
that may be outside
of their norm.

56:13.280 --> 56:16.363
Sort of like, um, you know, one
of those old wildlife explorers

56:16.440 --> 56:19.922
bringing an exotic spice
back to the world.

56:20.000 --> 56:21.440
I sound like
such a douche right now.

56:21.480 --> 56:23.005
(LAUGHS)

56:23.080 --> 56:25.970
Robin Sands, rock and roll
spice merchant.

56:26.040 --> 56:29.010
(LAUGHING)
It's kind of Excellent..

56:29.080 --> 56:30.650
You're funny, you know that?

56:32.400 --> 56:33.561
Why are you so surprised?

56:33.640 --> 56:35.760
Why is everybody always
surprised when I crack a joke?

56:35.960 --> 56:38.566
Well, you know, obituary writer.

56:38.640 --> 56:40.483
I'm not, like, tortured
and tormented.

56:40.560 --> 56:42.369
I'm just gainfully employed.

56:42.640 --> 56:45.291
I mean, there's, like,
a voyeuristic quality to it

56:45.360 --> 56:46.600
that I find really interesting.

56:46.640 --> 56:49.849
I'm... I have a backstage
pass to somebody else's life.

56:49.920 --> 56:51.729
Okay, so what's
the career trajectory

56:51.800 --> 56:53.086
for an obituary writer?

56:53.160 --> 56:54.696
Do you hope to, like,
write about famous people

56:54.720 --> 56:56.210
when they eventually die or...

56:56.280 --> 56:59.727
No. No. (STAMMERS)

56:59.800 --> 57:01.723
I'm really good with
where I'm at right now.

57:02.800 --> 57:04.529
(CLICKING TONGUE)

57:05.120 --> 57:07.088
Oh, no.
What?

57:07.160 --> 57:08.366
No. No, no.

57:08.440 --> 57:11.842
This is not healthy,
for you to lie while you're...

57:11.920 --> 57:13.922
I know it's not
technically a date,

57:14.000 --> 57:16.606
but don't lie at the
beginning of a relationship.

57:16.680 --> 57:18.842
Harriet, wha...
What are you doing?

57:18.920 --> 57:20.285
(LAUGHS) What are
you doing here?

57:20.360 --> 57:21.600
I am...

57:21.680 --> 57:23.523
Did she tell you
she wants to be a writer?

57:23.680 --> 57:24.806
Yes, she is a writer.

57:24.920 --> 57:28.766
No, no. A real writer.
She wants to be an essayist.

57:28.880 --> 57:29.927
Harriet, don't do that.

57:30.000 --> 57:31.047
An essayist is someone

57:31.120 --> 57:36.126
who has a unifying
view, a worldview.

57:36.200 --> 57:39.761
Tell me something, Anne,
what is your...

57:40.280 --> 57:43.045
What are your collection
of essays saying?

57:44.840 --> 57:47.081
I don't know.

57:47.960 --> 57:50.201
Well, I don't believe you.
Do you believe her?

57:50.360 --> 57:51.416
You know what, Anne,
let's get out of here.

57:51.440 --> 57:52.521
No, no. Ms. Sherman,

57:52.600 --> 57:54.170
I really am just
looking for an answer.

57:54.280 --> 57:56.681
What is it that you want
to say in your essays?

57:57.240 --> 57:58.571
(SIGHS)

57:58.760 --> 58:00.888
Nothing. I don't want
to say anything.

58:00.960 --> 58:02.325
I have nothing
interesting to say.

58:02.440 --> 58:03.646
Oh, that's such bullshit.

58:03.720 --> 58:05.563
Harriet, knock it off.
No. Mmm-mmm.

58:05.640 --> 58:08.450
Don't you protect her like
some kind of wounded animal.

58:08.520 --> 58:10.090
No, no. If she wants
to be a writer,

58:10.160 --> 58:12.367
she has got to learn
to express her mind.

58:12.440 --> 58:14.240
You don't have to listen
to any of this, Anne.

58:14.440 --> 58:16.568
No, don't listen.
He's right.

58:16.840 --> 58:19.207
Don't listen. Go back in your
little bubble. No problem.

58:19.280 --> 58:20.770
Man, what is your problem?

58:25.960 --> 58:29.601
Ambition neutered
by self-doubt.

58:33.280 --> 58:34.441
Desire.

58:34.720 --> 58:38.770
Desire. Desire is what
my essays are about.

58:39.280 --> 58:40.611
It's, um...

58:41.640 --> 58:45.611
It's, uh... They're about
the sacrifice that we make

58:46.440 --> 58:48.761
in order to fulfill our desires.

58:50.000 --> 58:51.968
(SCOFFS) I'm so sorry I asked.

58:52.040 --> 58:53.451
Oh, fuck off. All right.

58:53.520 --> 58:55.522
Oh, life! I see some life!

58:55.600 --> 58:57.364
You bait me into
talking about shit

58:57.440 --> 58:58.726
that I don't want to talk about

58:58.800 --> 59:00.529
and then when I talk
about it, you mock me!

59:00.640 --> 59:01.721
What's wrong with you?

59:01.800 --> 59:03.086
Why don't you calm down?

59:03.160 --> 59:05.367
I just want to understand
what is in your essays

59:05.440 --> 59:06.646
and what you're trying to do.

59:06.720 --> 59:08.563
They're just so very
precious it seems.

59:08.640 --> 59:09.801
Oh, really? Are they?

59:10.760 --> 59:16.051
I... I need. I yearn.
I long. I deserve.

59:16.120 --> 59:17.884
Oh... And the world,

59:17.960 --> 59:20.406
the world is so much
harder than you've dreamed.

59:20.560 --> 59:22.403
And my trophies...
I don't have any trophies.

59:22.480 --> 59:24.642
I was supposed
to get trophies. (SCOFFS)

59:26.920 --> 59:30.163
You know, in hindsight,
this all makes some sense.

59:31.920 --> 59:34.844
Oh, really? Go ahead.
Should be good.

59:36.640 --> 59:38.961
I think you're trying
to write about yourself

59:39.040 --> 59:42.169
and you haven't got a goddamn
idea of the subject matter.

59:46.720 --> 59:48.370
Go fuck yourself, Harriet.

